: 68.61, "y1": 6.91}, {"x0": 10.46, "y0": 32.01, "x1": 46.72, "y1": 34.26}, {"x0": 9.07, "y0": 29.92, "x1": 14.57, "y1": 33.8}, {"x0": 9.68, "y0": 8.55, "x1": 42.93, "y1": 28.74}, {"x0": 9.07, "y0": 75.9, "x1": 55.05, "y1": 91.4}], "full_text": "Radiology\nAxial contrast-enhanced CT demonstrates\nacute necrotizing pancreatitis:\n1. lack of enhancement (low attenuation) in the\npancreatic head and proximal body (dashed\narrow)\n2. Surrounding fat stranding\n3. Free fluid\n( Note :normal enhancement (high attenuation)\nof the distal pancreatic body for comparison)\nAcute appendicitis\nPresentation\n1. Periumbilical abdominal pain localizing to the right lower quadrant\n2. Nausea, vomiting.\n3. Fever.\n4. Abdominal tenderness—maximal over McBurney’s point, guarding, rigidity.\n5. Raised inflammatory markers.\nKey imaging\nUS\n▪ Generally, the first imaging test of choice due to its safety. (esp. children and\npregnant females).\n▪ Good positive but not a good negative test.\nContrast-enhanced CT\n▪ The most accurate diagnostic tool in adults .\n▪ For children, it is typically reserved for cases where US is inconclusive or\ncomplications are suspected (rupture, abscess, phlegmon)\n▪ Identification of alternative diagnoses when a patient's symptoms mimic\nappendicitis\nNormal compressible\nappendix on transverse US\n(a) 4 mm diameter on\ncompression\n(b) 3mm diameter after\ncompression\n98"}